
Just loop through items	forEach()
Transform each item	map()
Get only matching items	filter()
Find one specific item	find()
Check if item exists	includes()
Check any item passes	some()
Check all items pass	every()
Sum or combine all	reduce()
Sort data	sort()
Add/remove elements	push(), pop(), shift(), unshift(), splice()
Copy or merge	slice(), concat()
Flatten nested arrays	flat()

// ======================================
// ðŸ§  JavaScript Array Methods â€” Quick Revision Notes
ðŸ”¹ 1. forEach()
// What it does: Loops through each item in an array.
// When to use: When you just want to do something for each item (no return needed).
arr.forEach(item => console.log(item));
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 2. map()
What it does: Creates a new array by transforming each element.
When to use: When you want to modify items and return a new array.
const doubled = arr.map(num => num * 2);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 3. filter()
What it does: Returns a new array with elements that match a condition.
When to use: When you need only certain elements.
const even = arr.filter(num => num % 2 === 0);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 4. find()
What it does: Returns the first element that matches a condition.
When to use: When you want to find one specific item (object, user, etc.).
const user = users.find(u => u.id === 1);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 5. includes()
What it does: Checks if an array contains a specific value.
When to use: For existence checks (true/false).
arr.includes('apple'); // true or false
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 6. some()
What it does: Returns true if any item matches a condition.
When to use: When only one match is enough.
arr.some(num => num > 10);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 7. every()
What it does: Returns true if all items match a condition.
When to use: To ensure all elements meet a rule.
arr.every(num => num > 0);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 8. reduce()
What it does: Combines all elements into one value (e.g., sum).
When to use: To calculate totals or aggregate data.
const total = arr.reduce((sum, n) => sum + n, 0);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 9. sort()
What it does: Sorts array elements (changes original array).
When to use: When you need ordered data.
arr.sort((a, b) => a - b); // numeric sort
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 10. push() / pop()
What they do: Add or remove elements at the end.
When to use: For stack-like operations.
arr.push('item'); // add
arr.pop();        // remove last
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 11. unshift() / shift()
What they do: Add or remove elements at the beginning.
When to use: For queue-like operations.
arr.unshift('start');
arr.shift();
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 12. slice()
What it does: Copies part of an array into a new one.
When to use: To extract without changing the original.
arr.slice(1, 3);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 13. splice()
What it does: Adds or removes elements in place.
When to use: To modify the original array.
arr.splice(1, 2, 'newItem');
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 14. concat()
What it does: Combines multiple arrays into one.
When to use: To merge arrays.
arr.concat(otherArr);
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ 15. flat()
What it does: Flattens nested arrays.
When to use: When you have arrays inside arrays.
arr.flat(2);
